The course  focuses on Estonian and Baltic-German literary contacts, also touching upon the existence of other literary traditions in historical Baltic cultural space (Neo-Latin poetry in the 17th century, Russian literature in the 19th century ect). The Baltic-German literature is viewed within the framework of the general sociocultural background, as well as in the context of other arts (fine art, journalism, essay tradition ect).Objectives/eesmärkid:  The aim of the course is to provide an introduction to the history of Baltic-German literature and culture, and to outline ist relevance to the emergence and development of Estonian literature.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  Students will acquire knowledge about Baltic-German culture and literature from  the13th century to the year 1939 and will be also able to see connections between Estonian and Europe literature in general. Students have to read 3-5 books of Baltic-German literature of their own choice.
